# ADR 0011: Shared Content Model

Status: Accepted

Date: 2026-07-25

Decision Makers

- Mato Cashew Platform Team

---

# Context

The Mato Cashew Platform is designed as a Content-First Platform.

The platform will contain multiple publishable content types including:

- Knowledge
- Articles
- Recipes
- Guides
- FAQs
- Downloads
- Industry News
- Research Papers
- Future educational resources

If every content type defines its own fields independently, the platform will quickly accumulate duplicated models, inconsistent metadata, and repeated business logic.

Examples of duplicated fields include:

- title
- slug
- description
- author
- tags
- SEO
- hero image
- publish date

Duplicating these fields across multiple models increases maintenance costs and makes future CMS integration more difficult.

---

# Decision

The platform adopts a Shared Content Model.

All publishable content types must inherit from a common base content model.

Each specific content type should extend the shared model by adding only its own domain-specific fields.

---

# Base Content Model

Every publishable content type should contain the following core properties.

Identity

- title
- slug

Content

- description
- excerpt
- body

Publishing

- author
- publishedAt
- updatedAt
- draft
- featured

Media

- heroImage

Classification

- tags

SEO

- seo

Localization

- language

---

# Derived Content Types

The following models extend the shared base model.

Knowledge

Additional fields

- category
- readingTime
- relatedProducts

---

Article

Additional fields

- category
- source
- references

---

Recipe

Additional fields

- ingredients
- preparationTime
- cookingTime
- servings
- nutrition

---

Guide

Additional fields

- difficulty
- estimatedTime
- downloadableResources

---

FAQ

Additional fields

- question
- answer
- category

---

Download

Additional fields

- file
- version
- fileSize
- format

---

# Architectural Principles

## Reuse

Common metadata must never be duplicated.

---

## Consistency

All publishable content should follow the same publishing workflow.

---

## Extensibility

New content types should extend the shared model rather than creating independent models.

---

## Separation of Concerns

Content models define data.

Services implement business logic.

Components render content.

Pages compose layouts.

---

# Benefits

The shared model provides:

- Consistent metadata
- Shared publishing workflow
- Easier SEO implementation
- Better CMS integration
- Reduced code duplication
- Cleaner TypeScript interfaces
- Reusable services
- Simpler search indexing

---

# Example Hierarchy

BaseContent

├── Knowledge

├── Article

├── Recipe

├── Guide

├── FAQ

└── Download

Every child model inherits common fields and introduces only domain-specific properties.

---

# Search

Because every content type shares the same base model, the search engine can index all content consistently.

Search fields include:

- title
- description
- excerpt
- tags
- author

Additional fields may be indexed depending on the content type.

---

# SEO

Every publishable content type must support:

- SEO title
- Meta description
- Canonical URL
- Open Graph
- Twitter Card
- Structured Data

SEO metadata should follow a unified schema.

---

# CMS Compatibility

The shared model enables future migration to:

- Headless CMS
- REST API
- GraphQL
- Database
- External content sources

without redesigning the application architecture.

---

# Future Expansion

The shared model should support additional content types including:

- Market Reports
- Case Studies
- White Papers
- Research Papers
- Video Lessons
- Learning Modules
- Interactive Tutorials

without changing existing content models.

---

# Consequences

Positive

- Reduced duplication
- Better maintainability
- Cleaner architecture
- Consistent publishing
- Easier testing
- Better scalability

Trade-offs

- Slightly more initial design effort
- Requires developers to understand inheritance
- Additional planning before implementation

These trade-offs are acceptable because they support long-term maintainability.

---

# Implementation Guidelines

Developers should:

- Create one BaseContent interface.
- Extend BaseContent for every publishable content type.
- Keep shared metadata inside the base model.
- Avoid redefining inherited properties.
- Keep business logic inside services.

